  "business_context": "Campaign records hold the structure of any organized outbound effort: a tradeshow, an email blast, a direct-mail solicitation, a webinar series, a multi-channel product launch, a year-end appeal. Each campaign has a target audience (the people it goes out to), a channel mix (the means of reach), a budget (the cost), and an outcome (the conversions, opportunities, or donations attributed to it). The most-watched metric on a campaign is ROI — revenue / donations divided by cost. Campaign hierarchies (parent campaign + child campaigns) are common: a \"Year-End Appeal 2025\" parent campaign with child campaigns for \"Email Blast 1,\" \"Email Blast 2,\" \"Direct Mail Drop,\" \"Phone-a-thon,\" each tracking sub-channel performance against the same overall fundraising goal. In nonprofit deployments, campaigns drive appeals tracking, grant-cycle tracking, and event fundraising. In B2B sales, campaigns drive lead-generation attribution and pipeline-source analysis. When interviewing clients, surface \"Campaign\" by asking how they organize their outbound efforts and whether they need to attribute revenue or donations back to specific campaigns: yes if they run campaigns regularly and care about source attribution; less critical if all outreach is one-off relationship- driven activity. Campaign-Member junction records (separate entry) capture which contacts are in each campaign with what status.",
